message: Congresswoman Val Demings wants to hear from you. Join her for a Town Hall in Apopka on April 11th from 7pm-9pm. It will be hosted in the Council Chambers of the Apopka City Hall
Join Congresswoman Val Demings for a legislative update and town hall in Eatonville on Tuesday, May 30.
NA
NA

A day I will never forget. Being sworn into the U.S. House of Representatives.  My promise to my constituents and the people in Central Florida: Every day I'm here, I'm going to fight for fairness. I'm going to fight for equal protection under the law, and continue to protect and serve you.
NA
"I am leaving, but I am not going to be QUIET."  Thank you Mr. Vice President.
We are hearing from our constituents that the Affordable Care Act is saving lives.   We want to know, how has the ACA helped you?   Share your story with us.

As we wait to learn more details about the shooting at the Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood International airport our prayers are with the victims and their families. We thank the first responders for their bravery in the face of danger.

This senseless shooting, like the one we saw at Pulse Night Club in Orlando and the countless others around our Nation where innocent victims are targeted, is hard to comprehend.  Today's shooting brings back painful memories of September 11, 2001, when I was assigned to lead the Orlando Police Department's Airport division at Orlando International Airport.  As we wait to learn more details about what led to this heinous act, we pray for the victims and their families, facing a horror that no family should ever have to.  We thank and commend the first responders and airport staff for their bravery in the face of danger.

LAW ENFORCEMENT APPRECIATION DAY.  As we celebrate the bravery of law enforcement officers all over our nation, I join Orlando in mourning the violent death of one of our own. COURAGE. PRIDE. COMMITMENT.

I join Orlando, the Orange County Sheriff‚Äôs Office and my Orlando Police Department family in mourning the violent death of one of our own and the death of a deputy killed in the line of duty.  I had the honor of working with Sgt. Debra Clayton for many years at the Orlando Police Department. Sgt. Clayton was a fine law enforcement officer, wife, and mother who served her community with pride and as a mentor to young women.  Gone, but never forgotten.
My first speech on the House Floor was not one I ever imagined giving.  We honor the life and legacy of Master Sgt. Deborah Clayton and Deputy Norman Lewis.   Gone, but never forgotten.

"I am asking you to hold fast to that faith written into our founding documents; that idea whispered by slaves and abolitionists; that spirit sung by immigrants and homesteaders and those who marched for justice; that creed reaffirmed by those who planted flags from foreign battlefields to the surface of the moon; a creed at the core of every American whose story is not yet written: Yes, we CAN. Yes, We DID. Yes, we CAN."  Thank you Mr. President for leading this country through some of its toughest times with courage, grace and strength. You will be remembered not just for your leadership, but your character.   Thank you for showing us that we are the ones who create the change, for empowering our young people to take control of their future, and encouraging all of us to work hard to protect the change you were able to create.  We are forever grateful for your service. Yes, we CAN.

Today I introduced an amendment that would protect seniors on Medicare from seeing changes to the price of their prescription drugs because of an ACA repeal.  With too many Floridians, and seniors across the nation struggling to make ends meet, I strongly believe that Congress can do more to make sure we do not go backwards.

"The world would be a different place if it were not for Martin Luther King Jr."   Thank you Congressman John Lewis for sharing your stories with the Freshman Class of the 115th Congress to honor Martin Luther King Jr. Day.
It is always an honor to hear Congressman John Lewis speak. We are grateful you took on the fight for civil rights, and that you continue to fight for justice.

Repealing the Affordable Care Act would put millions at risk of losing their health care, and millions more of losing their jobs.  I stood on the House Floor today to urge my colleagues to work to STRENGTHEN the ACA, not repeal it.

1.6 Million More Floridians now have access to quality health care because of the Affordable Care Act. These Floridians can't afford to lose access to that health care.   We must stand against the plan to Repeal & Replace ACA.
A beautiful tribute to my friend Master Sgt. Debra Clayton.  Gone, but never forgotten.

Today I voted to protect the Affordable Care Act.  Repealing #ACA without a plan to replace it is destructive and irresponsible.   I promise to continue to fight on behalf of Central Floridians, and all Americans, to ensure no one is stripped of their health care.
NA
It is hard to pick the most troubling thing to come out of the #DeVosHearing. No Mrs. DeVos, guns have no place in our schools.
As we say farewell to President Obama, let's not forget to thank him for the progress he fought for over the last 8 years.   Let's continue to thank him by protecting that progress.   #ThanksObama

I stopped by the Pine Hills Community Center to talk to this wonderful group of Seniors this morning.   My promise to them, and to all of you, is to protect Medicare, every part of it. Every senior deserves to retire with dignity and respect, Medicare is at the foundation of that. #ACAWorks #SaveACA

I spoke with News 6 this morning ahead of the Inauguration.   I know my constituents are looking to me and my colleagues to hold President Trump accountable.   We need to ensure that his agenda is one that is inclusive to all people. He needs to show us that he will work to unite this country.   The American people deserve to hear that today.

"I have no fear anymore. I'm not afraid of failure. I believe many women will not try to reach their full potential or get that corner office because they're afraid of failure and what that will mean about them. I would not be a member of Congress right now if I had been afraid of losing."

Republicans are on a mission to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act without a viable replacement and lives are at risk.   "The biggest and most definitive study of what happens to death rates when Medicaid coverage is expanded, published in the New England Journal of Medicine, found that for every 455 people who gained coverage across several states, one life was saved per year. Applying that figure to even a conservative estimate of 20 million losing coverage in the event of an ACA repeal yields an estimate of 43,956 deaths annually."  #ProtectACA
Headed back to the district. Ready for some warmer weather!

From the bottom of my heart, THANK YOU.  Thank you to everyone who was in the room, and those of you who were not. It's been a journey to get here and I'm so honored to represent Central Florida. I will always fight for you.

It was such an honor to have the family of Lt. Deborah Clayton, and the family of Deputy Norm Lewis with us at my swearing-in ceremony yesterday.  We presented them with Congressional flags that were flown over the Capitol in honor of Lt. Clayton and Deputy Lewis. To both families, our community continues to stand with you during these difficult times.   Gone, but never forgotten.
We must protect Melissa Nelson and the millions of other people who are insured under the Affordable Care Act.
Spending the afternoon at the Zora Neale Hurston Festival. Come join us!

We are continuing to monitor this situation closely here in Central Florida.  This afternoon I will be meeting with leaders from the Central Florida Muslim Community. We must stand united against this immoral and unconstitutional ban of Muslims.
Meeting with the Central Florida Muslim Community about President Trump's Executive Order Banning Refugees and Migrants from Muslim Countries

Over 200 people showed up for our community meeting at the Islamic Center of Orlando.   We had a productive and thoughtful discussion about the discriminatory bans put in place by President Trump.  This isn't a Muslim issue, this is an American issue.   Our community showed the Trump administration we stand united and ready to fight his extreme agenda.

Tonight I will stand in solidarity with House and Senate Democrats on the steps of the Supreme Court to condemn President Trump's Executive Order on Immigration.   You can watch it live here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=edXUK3wQdN4

Proud to stand with my Democratic Colleagues to speak out against President Trump's discriminatory order.   This order does make America "unsafe" and "inhumane." We will continue to fight it every step of the way.

Today I stood on the House Floor with Democrats to demand a vote to rescind President Trump's Executive Order on Immigration.  Keeping our nation and our borders safe is my number one priority, but this order does not accomplish that.

Serious questions have been raised by both Republicans and Democrats about the effectiveness of the wall in deterring or disrupting illegal border crossings.  The truth of the matter is that no one can tell us exactly how much it will cost taxpayers because we haven‚Äôt seen reliable cost estimates, which is why it is imperative that it be included in our Oversight Plan.

"Mama exhorted her children at every opportunity to ‚Äòjump at de sun.‚Äô We might not land on the sun, but at least we would get off the ground."  As we mark the beginning of Black History Month I start by paying tribute to local African American Pioneer Zora Neale Hurston and the town of Eatonville.   Eatonville, the nation's oldest incorporated black settlement, was home to Zora Neale Hurston.  Hurston, the first Black American Author to publish African-American Folklore, found her voice and wrote her greatest works in Eatonville.  https://demings.house.gov/media/press-releases/representative-val-demings-kicks-black-history-month-honoring-local-african
I proposed an amendment to make sure taxpayers, many who are already struggling to make ends meet, are not stuck with the cost of a proposed border-wall.
Nurses are some of our unsung heroes. Thank you to these Florida nurses from the Black Nurses Association for stopping by my office today!
Happy Birthday Rosa Parks. "Quiet Strength."

In the Homeland Security Committee Hearing this morning where we are questioning Secretary John Kelly on President Trump's executive order on immigration and plans to build a border wall.   You can watch the hearing here: https://homeland.house.gov/hearing/ending-crisis-americas-borders-path-security/

Today I questioned Homeland Security Secretary John Kelly during a Homeland Security Committee Hearing.  I asked about the use of data analytics when it comes to securing our boders, and what the Secretary thought needed to be changed about our vetting process.
Seniors deserve the right to retire with respect and dignity.  What would the #ACARepeal do to Seniors?
You can use your voice for good. Here's some examples on how to make sure your voice is heard.
JUSTICE is strong willed. It will continue to fight for its place in history.

During Black History Month it is important to honor some of the unsung heroes in our community like Mrs. Dudley.   "Her story is one that could be any of ours. We all have a role to play in helping to make our nation a better place. I am reminded of the song by Mahalia Jackson: ‚ÄúIf I can help somebody as I travel along, then my living will not be in vain.‚Äù
Early Valentine's Day surprise from the Sheriff. ‚ù§Ô∏è

"In valor there is hope."  Last year 66 officers were shot and killed in the line of duty, a 60% increase.   I stood today at the Law Enforcement Memorial with Congresswoman Gabby Giffords, Cpt. Mark Kelly, Sheriff Lupe Valdez, Chief Louis Dekmar, and Chief Jeffrey Hadley to honor Law Enforcement killed by gun fire.   I'm proud to support Americans for Responsible Solutions new effort, "Law Enforcement Coalition for Common Gun Sense."  We respect the 2nd amendment and the rights of responsible gun owners. This is about keeping guns out of the hands of the wrong people and preventing senseless acts of gun violence.

General Michael Flynn's resignation is a step in the right direction, but this only further confirms the need for an investigation into the Trump administration's ties to Russia.   I join my Democratic colleagues on the Oversight  Committee in calling for an investigation.   The American people deserve answers.
In the spirit of Valentine's Day, a story about how the Sheriff and I first met.   Don't forget to spread some love today!

Proud to be a co-sponsor on the bipartisan WINGMAN bill that will help Veterans better access their benefits.   These changes are needed to help speed up the claims process and I hope my colleagues in the Senate take swift action and pass this bill.
My Valentine.

The American people deserve answers and transparency. That can only come from a bipartisan, independent investigation into this administrations ties to Russia.   I urge my Republican colleagues to join us in calling for a thorough investigation. I know they understand the gravity of this issue, and believe it is our duty to work together to keep our nation safe.

Thank you to Georgetown Law for hosting the new members of the Congressional Black Caucus tonight.  Proud to stand with Representatives Gregory Meeks and Stacey Plaskett and my freshman colleagues, Rep. Lisa Blunt Rochester and Rep. Anthony Brown.
#tbt to the Women's March. We won't stop fighting for what is right.
Always applicable words of wisdom from Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. this Black History Month.
I had a great time celebrating Arab American culture today. Standing together we embrace the diversity that makes our community great.

Have you signed up for my newsletter yet?  It's the best way to stay connected, informed and up to date on what is happening in my office, in the district and in DC.  You can sign up by visiting demings.house.gov.

Spent the morning touring the Air Traffic Control towers at Orlando International Airport.  Fascinating to see what goes into making the airport run so smoothly. Thank you to the National Air Traffic Controllers Association for the warm welcome and for the outstanding job you do EVERYDAY.

Access to quality health care is critical, and it was great to see the work being done in Orlando at the DaVita Central Florida Dialysis center. Thank you to the patients, nurses and administrators for sharing your stories with me this afternoon.
By refusing to stand up, she stood up for civil rights. Today I honor the First Lady of the Civil Rights Movement, Rosa Parks. #BlackHistoryMonth

We are urging ICE to issue guidance making clear to ICE officers, special agents, and attorneys that victims of domestic violence should have no fear of seeking justice in our court systems.  Recent events have encouraged fear and run counter to decades of work to build relationships between law enforcement and victims of violent crime.
I'm joining my Democratic Colleagues on Homeland Security in demanding answers from DHS about the latest immigration executive order.  The American people deserve answers.
NA
Hope you can join us Sunday in Orlando for a Legislative Update and Town Hall on the Affordable Care Act.   There is a lot happening in Washington and I want you to be a part of the conversation.
Thank you to the Black Business Investment Fund. I'm honored to receive the Community Leadership Award.
Thank you to the Broward County Democratic Black Caucus for inviting me to speak to honor Black History Month.   We must continue to stay motivated and focused on the real issues.
ICYMI:Join me today in Orlando for a town hall on the Affordable Care Act. Starts at 3pm at Dr. Phillips High School.
Affordable Care Act Town Hall

Changing your government happens from the ground up. Thank you to everyone who came out to our Town Hall and for being a part of the conversation.   Thank you to our panelists: Jason Altmire from Florida Blue, Michael Griffin from Adventist Health Systems, and Anne Packham from Primary Access Network.  I will continue to fight to protect the affordable care act. Every American deserves the right to have access to quality health care that's affordable.
The system should protect our most vulnerable.   My interview with News 13's Political Connections last week to talk about the latest on President Trump's travel ban, immigration practices and more.

What I heard Sunday from constituents, and what we continue to hear, is that we cannot repeal the Affordable Care Act.  People's lives depend on having access to affordable, quality health care. #ProtectOurCare

I‚Äôm honored to have Christine Leinonen as my guest to President Trump's joint address tonight.   Christine's son Christopher died in the Pulse Night club shooting.   ‚ÄúMy son‚Äôs killer was not an undocumented immigrant."  I hope President Trump will listen to her message, along with the other victims and survivors of Pulse.  http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/political-pulse/os-demings-leinonen-trump-address-20170228-story.html

Christine Leinonen and I sat down for an interview with CNN this afternoon ahead of President Trump's speech.   We are hoping to hear him talk about what he's going to do at home, to prevent situations like Pulse.
I wore white tonight with my female colleagues to stand with women across the nation. We are UNITED in the fight for equal pay, equal treatment and equal representation. #JointSession

Lucy Burns, born 1879, was the cofounder of the Congressional Union for Women Suffrage, later the National Woman's Party.  Burns was a leading activist in the Women's Suffrage movement, arrested 6 times, serving more prison time than any other suffragist.   We honor Burns and the countless other women who lead with courage. #WomensHistoryMonth
Prayers for a speedy recovery Sgt. Stelter!   Thank you to all the men and women in uniform who risk their lives everyday to protect ours.
In Florida's 10th Congressional district alone 64,600 people insured through the Affordable Care Act stand to lose their insurance if the ACA is repealed.

"I don't think a lot about being in the minority party because right and wrong doesn't change. We can be a loud voice in calling for investigations, calling for oversight, calling for transparency and I think we've seen some of our Republican colleagues calling for the same things."
Welcome To Orlando President Trump, A City Stronger Because Of Its Diversity.
On this day in 1845 Florida joined the union. Happy Birthday, Florida! I'm a proud life-long resident. ‚òÄÔ∏èÌ†ºÌº¥
A beautiful tribute to the 49. #OrlandoStrong #OrlandoUnited

Excited to participate in Delta Sigma Theta's 28th annual "Delta Days in the Nation's Capital."   Today's discussion, "Advocacy in Action: one nation of two? After the Election, the National and Local Priorities."
Are you insured by the Affordable Care Act?   Tell us YOUR story about how the ACA has helped you, as we fight to protect it from being repealed.

"When we talk about women's issues, we're talking about America's issues. Every man should want their mothers, their sisters, their aunts, and all the women in their lives that they care about to succeed and have the resources that they need. They're not just women's issues, because women touch every man's life in some way."

What is at Stake with the GOP's Plan to Repeal the Affordable Care Act?   ‚ùå You will be expected to pay MORE out of pocket, for LESS coverage.  ‚ùå Millions of Seniors covered under Medicaid expansion will lose their coverage and be forced to pay higher premiums.  ‚ùå Planned Parenthood will no longer be able to provide necessary health care services for the most vulnerable women.

How Long?  The people who need coverage the most, the people depending on this President the most, the middle class, working families, and the working poor will be left behind by this plan to dismantle the Affordable Care Act.
A great meeting today with local firefighters from Orlando and Reedy Creek. Proud to support the efforts of the International Association of Fire Fighters.

I'm wearing red today in solidarity with women all across the world.   I celebrate the women who paved the way so I could serve in law enforcement and now in Congress.   We continue the fight for the women who come after us. #InternationalWomensDay

Chief Penny Harrington was the first female to achieve the rank of police chief, appointed in 1985 as Chief of the Portland Police Bureau.  She was a dedicated public servant, and a pioneer who paved the way for countless women in law enforcement.   Being a first is not easy. I honor Chief Harrington today on #InternationalWomensDay and thank her for paving the way for future female police chiefs, like myself.
We are still in red, and staying late into the night on Oversight Committee to stand up for our federal workforce and DC's public schools.

#tbt "I worked for 7 male Chiefs, had I not had the courage to take a risk and believe in something I had never seen before, I would have never been appointed Chief."  Don't let fear hold you back from achieving your dreams.

It is so important for me to honor all of the women that helped make Orlando the community it is today.  Edna S. Hargrett is one of them. Mrs. Hargrett was the choral director at Jones High School in Orlando for 33 years.   Her choir was recognized regionally and nationally for their classical and gospel renditions. She was a beloved teacher who taught her students to ‚Äúthink superior, be superior, and sing superior-plus.‚Äù   We honor Mrs. Edna Hargrett for her tireless commitment to excellence and education this #WomensHistoryMonth.

When we started in Congress our Freshman Class didn't focus on our differences, we focused on our similarities. Our class is committed to civility and working together where we can, when we can.   Joined my colleague, Representative Jack Bergman for an important discussion at the Bipartisan Policy Center tonight. Looking forward to continuing building these important relationships.
An early birthday surprise from my staff before I head back to Orlando. I'm blessed!

"I have seen the effects of good government, and the effects of bad government. When I was appointed chief of police crime was at an all-time high in Orlando and I believe tough times give us the the greatest opportunity to serve."

"In general, Floridians who are older, with lower incomes and live in rural areas will fare worse under the AHCA than they did under Obamacare, the Kaiser analysis shows, while those who are younger, with higher incomes and who live in urban areas will be better off."
I'm pleased to know the victims, families, and first responders will benefit from these funds. I couldn't be more proud of how our community responded in the face of tragedy.

This report from the non-partisan CBO confirms what we already knew to be true, millions of Americans will lose health insurance, hardworking families will be forced to pay higher premiums, and Medicaid recipients will suffer greatly.    As Republicans recklessly work to push through this plan, the people who need it the most, working families, seniors, and children stand to lose the most.   The GOP plan is not better than the Affordable Care Act and Republicans know it.

The facts are simple and cannot be denied: American's will pay more for less coverage under the GOP's plan, working families and seniors will suffer the most, and millions stand to lose health care.   I joined Roland Martin this morning on News One to talk about why many Republican's are now abandoning their own plan, and how we can all do better.

This is an area where I believe we can work with the President, to enhance the lives of Central Floridians.  He has said he wants to invest in infrastructure, and I hope we will see action on these specific projects.
Once again, justice prevails.
Facts we can't ignore. #PayMoreForLess
Celebrating these women who blazed the trail in law enforcement. #WomensHistoryMonth

It was such an honor to speak at the 22nd Annual RAFMAN Club Foundation and Valencia College Foundation Scholarship Banquet last night.   Thank you for your service and your commitment to lifting up the next generation.

What's at stake with the ACA Repeal? Services for children with disabilities.  Meet Sean and Angie from Orlando: Sean and Angie have six children, five of whom have special needs.   One of their children is deaf, but because of the ACA she was able to undergo surgery to give her hearing in one ear.   Another one of their children is blind, but because of the ACA she has the possibility of undergoing a cornea transplant.   Under the new plan, their future looks different. A lot of the benefits and services the children receive will be cut completely.  "We do not get "Handouts", like some in the GOP might accuse us of. We are just trying to make our children's lives better."  This family is one of many reasons I'm working to protect the ACA.
Last night I joined a few of my colleagues from the Congressional Black Caucus on the House Floor to talk about what we have to lose by repealing the Affordable Care Act.  Progress will be lost.

What‚Äôs at stake with the ACA repeal? Affordable coverage for breast cancer survivors.  One of my constituents, Monie, has been battling breast cancer and other health issues for 23 years.  She almost lost her home 22 years ago because she was paying a monthly premium of $1200.  Because of the ACA she was able to gain access to quality and affordable health care, despite being a cancer survivor.  Now she is worried that its replacement will put her at risk of losing coverage, her business, and possibly her home.  ‚ÄúThis could mean a death sentence for me and many others.‚Äù  For Monie's family and others, I will fight to protect the #ACA.

Feeling encouraged after talking to this group of Evans High School students.  They are members of the JROTC and in Washington for their spring break. Evans High School and students, doing GREAT things! The future looks bright!

What‚Äôs at stake with the ACA repeal? Mental health services for young adults.  Terri, one of my constituents, has a 24-year-old son who suffers from schizophrenia.  Because of the ACA she has been able to keep her son on her insurance, which is the only way he was been able to receive treatment.  "My son is doing well today and I'm not sure he would even be alive if I hadn't had the ACA to help me financially afford his very expensive care. I've had tremendous out-of-pocket expenses but being able to keep my son on my insurance was a life-saver for our whole family."  For Terri's family, and others, I will fight to protect the ACA.

What‚Äôs at stake with the ACA repeal? Services for people with pre-existing conditions.   Christine, one of my constituents, is covered through the ACA because of her pre-existing condition of breast cancer.   The ACA protects her from being excluded from coverage if she ever needs to change her insurance in the future.       ‚ÄúI like that the ACA does not cap lifetime benefits, if my cancer ever comes back. It also keeps emergency rooms from being the first line of health care.‚Äù  For Christine, and other cancer survivors, I will fight for to protect the ACA.
I have Chantalle from Spelman College shadowing me this morning. What a day to be on Capitol Hill!
What family should not receive quality health care?   Every family deserves coverage. Every family deserves to be protected. Every family is worth fighting for.

I loved having this group of teen girls from Apopka‚Äôs LANES Program in my office today.   LANES stands for: LOVING. ASSISTING. NURTURING. EDUCATING. SUPPORTING.   It‚Äôs our responsibility to ensure we are doing everything we can to lift up the next generation.
No matter when they decide to go to the floor for a vote on the ACA repeal, I will vote my conscience, and what my constituents have overwhelmingly told me they want.

What‚Äôs at stake with the ACA repeal? Young adults left without coverage.   Eliza, a recent college graduate and one of my constituents, is currently on her parents‚Äô health insurance thanks to the Affordable Care Act. Like most young adults struggling to find work after college, Eliza is worried she‚Äôll be left without health insurance if the ACA is repealed.   ‚ÄúWithout the ACA most people wouldn‚Äôt be able to stay on their parents‚Äô health insurance, and most young adults wouldn‚Äôt have insurance at all.‚Äù   I am fighting to protect the ACA so that young adults like Eliza aren‚Äôt left uninsured.

Overwhelmingly the American people have voiced their opposition to the Republican‚Äôs plan to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act.   The voices of the American people were heard, and we will not be forced to live through the harmful effects this bill would have had.   Republicans have been promising to replace the Affordable Care Act with something better for seven years, but the destructive bill that they proposed would force people to pay more for less coverage, erase protections for preexisting conditions, deny veterans additional benefits, force seniors to pay more for care and prescriptions, and shorten the life of Medicare.   I will continue to stand strong for my constituents in my fight to protect the Affordable Care Act.

We have heard from over 1,000 constituents in the past 24 hours who overwhelmingly opposed this bill.  Your voices were heard, your concerns have been noted. I will continue to work for you, to make the Affordable Care Act the best it can be.  I'm headed back to Orlando feeling GOOD and knowing that the work never ends. This is a victory for the American people.

What I've learned in this healthcare debate is that it is really about what's right and what's wrong.  My interview yesterday on MSNBC about moving forward to make the Affordable Care Act the best it can be.
Joining my colleagues from the Congressional Black Caucus on the House Floor tonight to talk about the harmful effects of President Trump's proposed budget. Tune in here---->

When I think about a vision for the future of America, I personally think about a vision that exceeds our wildest expectations.   A vision where every boy and girl, regardless of the color of their skin, their gender, their religion, sexual orientation, where they live or how much money their parents have in the bank, has an opportunity to succeed.  President Trump's budget lacks that vision.

If we are going to put America first, we need to put the American people first.  In 1965 President Lyndon Johnson commissioned a group to study crime in America.  It found that "slum schools" must be given enough resources to make them as good as schools elsewhere to enable them to compensate from the various handicaps suffered by the "slum child", in order to rescue him from his environment.   We are still trying to rescue children that this child represents from their at-risk environment.
Why I'm voting NO on S.J. Res 34. We must protect #BroadBandPrivacy.

It's incredibly disappointing to see President Trump take this step to rollback critical environmental protections.   The President has made another false promise, claiming this Executive Order will help the economy and bring back jobs in struggling communities, but this only promises to do further harm to communities.    Congress and this Administration has an obligation to protect our environment for the generations to come, and that starts by acknowledging that Climate Change is a real threat and promising to continue to address it.

So many of the women in our lives that influence us the most don‚Äôt make it into the history books.   The woman who shaped my life was my mother, Mrs. Elouise Woods Butler.    My mother worked as a maid to make sure her seven children had an opportunity to succeed.   She never graduated high school, but always pushed me to pursue higher education. She taught me that with hard work and perseverance, I could see MY dreams come true. She taught me to treat people with respect, and to "never grow tired of doing good."  This #WomensHistoryMonth I honor her, and all of the other unsung heroes who have helped shape our lives.
Great to meet with these advocates from the Alzheimer's Association of Central Florida. We still have a long ways to go on Alzheimer's research, but I will never stop working for a cure.
Did you receive the Demings Connection?  Stay up to date with everything happening in D.C. and the District by signing up for our eNewsletter: https://demings.house.gov/contact/newsletter

Ended #WomensHistoryMonth by launching our Women's Advisory Council in Orlando.   Looking forward to continuing these important discussions with this group of Central Florida Leaders.   We can never have enough women at the table, involved in high-level decision making and providing input on legislation that effects women in all areas of their lives.

We spent the morning worshiping with Senator Bill Nelson and Senator Cory Booker. Great to welcome them to my home church, Saint Mark AME, and to Macedonia Missionary Baptist Church and Saint John Missionary Baptist.
This Saturday, don't miss our Open House at our district office. Meet the staff and learn about the constituent services we have to offer. Hope to see you there!

Our District Office phones are currently experiencing issues, and are a part of a larger outage in the area.   We are sorry about any inconvenience this may have caused. Please call our DC phone line for any issues, the number is 202-225-2176.
Our phones are back up and working. We apologize for any inconvenience this may have caused.
Hatred and Fear took him away from us.  Love and Courage will sustain us.

The wage gap between men and women is still real.  54 years after we passed the Equal Pay Act, a woman still earns 80 cents for every dollar a man earns.  We can do better. Proud to be a co-sponsor on the Paycheck Fairness Act that would strengthen the Equal Pay Act and ensure women can challenge pay discrimination.  #EqualPayDay
"I have been pushing for and will continue to work to ensure a bipartisan and independent investigation into President Trump‚Äôs personal, professional, and financial ties to Russia."
Orlando, don't miss our Town Hall, next Wednesday, in Pine Hills.

Reducing or eliminating regulations on Silencers is a serious public safety concern. We cannot be silent, and let the gun lobby push to ease regulations on silencers.   I will not be silent, for my friend Lt. Deborah Clayton, the 49 victims of Pulse, or anyone who has died as a result of sensless gun violence.
Great to see Orange County Fire Chief Otto Drozd, and his colleagues in DC.  I'm proud of my son, who is an Orange County firefighter. Thank you all for making our community a safer place to live.

While I strongly condemn the cruel and evil actions of Assad on innocent women and children,  President Trump  should have obtained Congressional approval before using military force. May is National Foster Care Month.   Meet Shai'Robia Davis, a Florida native, who is shadowing me today. As a former Foster Care Counselor, I am proud to have her shadow me.   Resilient, smart, and determined, she entered foster care at 3-months old, and bounced around from home-to-home before aging out of the system at 18.   She is now studying Microbiology, and in her free time volunteers to help foster care youth. She attributes community support to her story being one of "success".  But many who age out of the foster care system are at a higher risk for poor educational outcomes, health issues, and homelessness. We must work to reverse these trends by creating permanent homes for young people in foster care faster. #FosterYouthVoices

Meet Eric Borrero, the Press Fellow in our Orlando office.   Eric is a survivor of the Pulse shooting and we wanted to share his story with you, in Eric's own words:   My name is Eric Borrero and I am a Pulse survivor.   The past year has felt as if I am living on a roller coaster that never ends. Life has been filled with many great highs, but are always accompanied by extreme lows. Through my lowest moments of last year, my support system and their positivity are what have brought me out of those dark spaces. That positivity enveloped me and has driven me to get involved in politics to, in some way, make a difference in the world, and bring love and inclusion to individuals and communities who feel excluded.  I am honored to intern with a Member of Congress who shares similar views and ideals of that of my own. It is an uplifting and enriching experience to work for an individual I can connect with and relate to, who is working for the benefit of her constituents.   Thank you, Congresswoman Val Demings and Team Demings for giving me this opportunity to share my experience and for helping me on the path to bring love and inclusion for all.
